To automatically generate a table of contents in a LaTeX document, you need to include the `\tableofcontents` command where you want the table of contents to appear, and use the `\section`, `\subsection`, `\subsubsection`, etc., commands to define the structure of your document. LaTeX will then automatically generate a table of contents based on these commands.

Here is a minimal working example:
```
\documentclass{article}

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction.

\section{Background}
This is the background.

\subsection{Subsection 1}
This is a subsection.

\subsection{Subsection 2}
This is another subsection.

\section{Conclusion}
This is the conclusion.

\end{document}
```
In this example, the `\tableofcontents` command is included at the beginning of the document, after `\begin{document}`. The `\section` and `\subsection` commands are used to define the structure of the document, and LaTeX automatically generates a table of contents based on this structure when the document is compiled.

To draw a chessboard in LaTeX based on a FEN notation, you can use the `chessboard` package. Here's a concise code that includes all the required commands and packages:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessboard}
\usepackage{skak}

\begin{document}

\newgame
\chessboard[setfen=\fen, pgfstyle=straightlines, linewidth=1pt, coloremphasis=\\boardgrey, color=black!20!white]

\end{document}
```

Replace `\fen` with your FEN notation. For example, if you want to set up the initial position, replace `\fen` with `startpos`. The chessboard will be drawn with greyed out squares for empty ones.

To install the package, you can use your TeX distribution's package manager (for example, TeX Live Utility for MacTeX, or TeXstudio's package manager on Linux).

This code should provide you with a basic chessboard setup based on the provided FEN notation. You can customize the appearance of the board by tweaking the options in the `\chessboard` command.

